abstract: Interviews with three dozen Democrats found exhaustion or lack of interest in the presidential candidate’s ancestry, reflecting a disconnect between some voters and Washington insiders.
snippet: Interviews with three dozen Democrats found exhaustion or lack of interest in the presidential candidate’s ancestry, reflecting a disconnect between some voters and Washington insiders.
lead_paragraph: LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. — Anna Stein, 44, doesn’t have a preferred presidential candidate yet for the 2020 Democratic nomination. But one thing is certain, she says: Elizabeth Warren’s handling of her Native American ancestry claims will not factor into her decision.

abstract: Former President Barack Obama has been counseling Democratic candidates on how to win the White House in 2020. But he has no plans to pick a favorite.
snippet: Former President Barack Obama has been counseling Democratic candidates on how to win the White House in 2020. But he has no plans to pick a favorite.
lead_paragraph: A secret meeting of former President Barack Obama’s financial backers convened in Washington early this month: Organized by David Jacobson and John Phillips, Mr. Obama’s former ambassadors to Canada and Italy, the group interviewed an array of 2020 presidential candidates and debated whether to throw their wealth behind one or two of them.

abstract: Candidates like Elizabeth Warren and Bernie Sanders were quick to praise New Yorkers who rebelled at the idea of giving tax breaks to a huge corporation.
snippet: Candidates like Elizabeth Warren and Bernie Sanders were quick to praise New Yorkers who rebelled at the idea of giving tax breaks to a huge corporation.
lead_paragraph: The decision by Amazon this week to abandon its planned headquarters in New York City tapped into one of the major themes of left-wing Democrats: that giant corporations — and in some cases the billionaires who run them — must be held to account for wage inequality, corporate greed and middle-class stagnation.

abstract: The Parkland shooting one year on. A princess vanishes. The Mars rover is dead. Investigating Ryan Adams. Dishes that don’t require recipes. And more.
snippet: The Parkland shooting one year on. A princess vanishes. The Mars rover is dead. Investigating Ryan Adams. Dishes that don’t require recipes. And more.
lead_paragraph: Welcome to the weekend. This week, we looked back on the Parkland school shooting in Florida and the journey of the Mars rover. We also investigated claims of manipulative behavior by the musician Ryan Adams and the escape attempt of a Dubai princess. There’s some amazing journalism here, take some time to catch up.

snippet: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
lead_paragraph: From the border wall fight to conflict with Iran, it’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the biggest stories you might have missed (and some links if you’d like to read further).
headline_main: On Politics: The Biggest Stories of the Week

abstract: Politicians’ memoirs, including those by Joe Biden and Kamala Harris, can give insight into their values.
snippet: Politicians’ memoirs, including those by Joe Biden and Kamala Harris, can give insight into their values.
lead_paragraph: (Updated June 26) More than 20 candidates have announced a bid for the presidency, and many of them will lay out their policy positions on Wednesday and Thursday during the first Democratic presidential debate. Often, politicians release books pegged to their announcements to drive interest and give voters a chance to get to know them. Here is a guide to some of those books, which can provide insight into the candidates’ priorities and worldview.

abstract: Don’t count on big changes. But the heated debates in Congress and on the 2020 campaign trail give clues about legislation to come.
snippet: Don’t count on big changes. But the heated debates in Congress and on the 2020 campaign trail give clues about legislation to come.
lead_paragraph: There was a brief period this month when it seemed that the midterm elections, which delivered control of the House to Democrats, might immediately shake up Americans’ income tax bills.

abstract: The slimmer refunds have been seized on by opponents of the tax cuts and Democratic lawmakers as proof that the Republican tax law did little to help average Americans.
snippet: The slimmer refunds have been seized on by opponents of the tax cuts and Democratic lawmakers as proof that the Republican tax law did little to help average Americans.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The Trump administration defended itself on Thursday amid a barrage of criticism from angry taxpayers who are disappointed that they are receiving smaller tax refunds after the 2017 Republican tax cuts.
